strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:

>It's not bizarre, it's the law. Basically, publishing a trade secret damages
>the owner of the secret. What is generous is giving innocent publishers of

And it is up to the owner to ensure that the secret remains secret. This
could be through not telling anyone, or giving anyone the remotest
opportunity to discover it. Or through ironclad legal agreements with
anyone that does see it to ensure that they do not divulge it.
For the owner to trust a trade secret to a shrinkwrapped license is like
telling all your your friends about your affair( accompanied by "Now
don't tell anyone else" of course), and then being
surprised when eveyone gets to know about it.
I do not know where the "generosity " comes in. I have the right to do
what I wish with information I obtain, unless I have explicitely given
up that right, or unless the government has explicitely removed that
right in the case of certain information. I certainly never gave up that
What is generous of the government was to place criminal sanctions
behind the civil trade secrets act.
